<seg id=1> U.S. Ambassador to China Called on the U.S. Government To Adopt A Constructive U.S.-China Policy </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> New York, March 6(xinhua correspondent Zhou Xisheng)-- James Sasser, U.S. Ambassador to China, delivered a speech at the luncheon hosted by National Committee on U.S-China Relations on March 6th in New York. He called on the U.S. government "to adopt a sustained, reliable and constructive U.S-China policy with a strategic view", and to solve the disputes with China through frank and comprehensive dialogues. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> James Sasser pointed out that the United States should rationally look at China's rising on the international arena no matter in the end of this century or in the next century and should take the set-up of a stable and healthy relations with China as an important opportunity in United State's foreign policy. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> On the question of human rights and intellectual property protection, the Ambassador pointed out that China had made considerable progress in these two aspects. </seg>
<seg id=5> He regarded that the Chinese people is now enjoying unprecedented freedom and democracy, and has taken positive and cooperative attitudes to intellectual property protection, which the United States should not ignore. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> James Sasser suggested the U.S. congress cancel the annual discussion on MFN treatment to China after China's entry into the WTO, and gives china the permanent MFN. </seg>
<seg id=7> He pointed out that the U.S. congress annual debate on this issue actually would do no good to the U.S. itself, but affect the U.S. businessmen's confidence to invest in China, and thus affect the vocation opportunity of the American people. </seg>
</p>
